<Window xmlns="https://github.com/avaloniaui"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        xmlns:d="http://schemas.microsoft.com/expression/blend/2008"
        xmlns:mc="http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/markup-compatibility/2006"
        mc:Ignorable="d" d:DesignWidth="800" d:DesignHeight="450"
        x:Class="JpegVisualDecoder.Views.AboutWindow"
        Title="AboutWindow">
    <ScrollViewer>
        <StackPanel Margin="24" Spacing="20">

            <!-- Title -->
            <TextBlock Text="JPEG Decoding Process"
                       FontSize="28"
                       FontWeight="Bold"/>

            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                JPEG decoding reconstructs an image from compressed data. The decoder
                reverses the steps used during encoding, converting compressed frequency
                data back into RGB pixel values that can be displayed on screen.
            </TextBlock>


            <!-- Pipeline Diagram -->
            <Border Padding="16" Background="#222" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="6">
                    <TextBlock Text="Decoding Pipeline"
                               FontWeight="Bold"
                               Foreground="White"/>

                    <TextBlock Foreground="White"
                               Text="Huffman Decode → Run-Length Expand → Dequantize → IDCT → Color Conversion → RGB Pixels"/>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>


            <!-- Lossy vs Lossless -->
            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                    <TextBlock Text="1. Lossless vs Lossy Compression"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Image compression methods fall into two categories: lossless and lossy.
                        Lossless compression preserves every bit of original information,
                        allowing perfect reconstruction of the image.
                    </TextBlock>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        JPEG uses lossy compression. Some visual information is discarded
                        during encoding to significantly reduce file size. The decoded
                        image is therefore an approximation of the original.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>


            <!-- Encoding Symmetry -->
            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                    <TextBlock Text="2. Encoding and Decoding Symmetry"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        The decoding process reverses the operations performed during
                        encoding. Entropy decoding reverses Huffman coding, dequantization
                        restores coefficient scales, and the inverse discrete cosine
                        transform converts frequency data back into spatial pixels.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>


            <!-- Run Length + Huffman -->
            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                    <TextBlock Text="3. Run-Length and Huffman Encoding"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        After quantization, many high-frequency coefficients become zero.
                        Run-length encoding compresses long sequences of zeros by storing
                        their length instead of each individual value.
                    </TextBlock>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        These symbols are then compressed using Huffman coding, which
                        assigns shorter bit sequences to common symbols and longer
                        sequences to rare ones.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <!-- Compression Math -->
            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                    <TextBlock Text="4. Compression Mathematics (DCT)"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        JPEG compression relies on the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT).
                        The transform converts an 8×8 pixel block into frequency
                        coefficients representing image patterns.
                    </TextBlock>

                    <Border Background="#222" Padding="12" CornerRadius="6">
                        <TextBlock Foreground="White"
                                   FontFamily="Consolas"
                                   TextWrapping="Wrap"
                                   Text="F(u,v) = 1/4 * C(u)C(v) Σ Σ f(x,y) cos((2x+1)uπ/16) cos((2y+1)vπ/16)"/>
                    </Border>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Low-frequency components describe smooth color transitions,
                        while high-frequency components represent fine details.
                        JPEG aggressively compresses high frequencies because
                        they are less noticeable to human vision.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">

                    <TextBlock Text="Zig-Zag Scan"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        JPEG stores DCT coefficients using a zig-zag traversal so that
                        low-frequency values appear first and long runs of zeros appear later.
                    </TextBlock>

                    <TextBlock FontFamily="Consolas"
                               TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        00 01 05 06 14 15 27 28 <LineBreak/>
                        02 04 07 13 16 26 29 42 <LineBreak/>
                        03 08 12 17 25 30 41 43 <LineBreak/>
                        09 11 18 24 31 40 44 53 <LineBreak/>
                        10 19 23 32 39 45 52 54 <LineBreak/>
                        20 22 33 38 46 51 55 60 <LineBreak/>
                        21 34 37 47 50 56 59 61 <LineBreak/>
                        35 36 48 49 57 58 62 63 <LineBreak/>
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">

                    <TextBlock Text="DCT 8×8 Block"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        JPEG divides the image into 8×8 pixel blocks. Each block is transformed
                        into frequency coefficients using the Discrete Cosine Transform.
                    </TextBlock>

                    <UniformGrid Rows="8" Columns="8" HorizontalAlignment="Center" Loaded="UniformGrid_Loaded"/>

                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">

                    <TextBlock Text="Quantization"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        Each DCT coefficient is divided by a value in a quantization table.
                        Larger divisors remove more detail but produce higher compression.
                    </TextBlock>

                    <Border Background="#222" Padding="10" CornerRadius="6">
                        <TextBlock Foreground="White"
                                   FontFamily="Consolas"
                                   Text="Quantized = round(DCT / QTable)"/>
                    </Border>

                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <!-- Color Space -->
            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">
                    <TextBlock Text="5. Color Space Conversion"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        JPEG stores images in the YCbCr color space rather than RGB.
                        Y represents brightness, while Cb and Cr represent color
                        differences.
                    </TextBlock>

                    <Border Background="#222" Padding="12" CornerRadius="6">
                        <StackPanel>
                            <TextBlock Foreground="White" FontFamily="Consolas"
                                       Text="R = Y + 1.402(Cr - 128)"/>
                            <TextBlock Foreground="White" FontFamily="Consolas"
                                       Text="G = Y - 0.344136(Cb - 128) - 0.714136(Cr - 128)"/>
                            <TextBlock Foreground="White" FontFamily="Consolas"
                                       Text="B = Y + 1.772(Cb - 128)"/>
                        </StackPanel>
                    </Border>

                    <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap">
                        During decoding, YCbCr values are converted back into RGB
                        pixels so the image can be displayed on a screen.
                    </TextBlock>
                </StackPanel>
            </Border>

            <Border Padding="16" Background="#f4f4f4" CornerRadius="8">
                <StackPanel Spacing="8">

                    <TextBlock Text="YCbCr to RGB"
                               FontSize="18"
                               FontWeight="Bold"/>

                    <StackPanel Orientation="Horizontal" Spacing="12">

                        <Border Background="#888888" Width="40" Height="40"/>
                        <Border Background="#88aaff" Width="40" Height="40"/>
                        <Border Background="#ff8888" Width="40" Height="40"/>

                        <TextBlock VerticalAlignment="Center"
                                   Text="→"/>

                        <Border Background="Red" Width="40" Height="40"/>
                        <Border Background="Green" Width="40" Height="40"/>
                        <Border Background="Blue" Width="40" Height="40"/>

                    </StackPanel>

                </StackPanel>
            </Border>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Window>
